## Lens 2: Economic Foundation
*Tab 2 of 4 · Financial structure and health · Sets the scale and sustainability context*

> **Core Question:** How big is your agency, how efficiently do you capture revenue, how profitable are you, and how financially stable is your operation?

---

### What This Lens Is Really Doing

Economic Foundation captures the **financial structure** of the business — not how well it is performing financially, but how it is financially constituted. The name is intentional: "foundation" implies something structural and stable. We are not evaluating financial performance against goals or trajectories. We are establishing **financial character**.

A $500K agency and a $5M agency are fundamentally different organisms even if they have identical margin percentages. Scale, efficiency, and liquidity together tell us what kind of financial organism we are dealing with — its economic carrying capacity, what it can bear, what it can invest, and how much runway it has for strategic moves.

---

### The 5 Story Beats

#### Beat 01 — Scale & Complexity
*How large is this agency and what does that imply about operational complexity?*

**Key Metrics:** Monthly revenue, annual revenue run rate

**Aha Moment:** Revenue scale is not just a size metric — it is a complexity indicator. A $500K agency is a micro-operation; a $5M agency is a mid-size enterprise. Each scale band implies different infrastructure requirements, team structures, client expectations, and management complexity. Scale sets the context for interpreting every other metric in this tab.

---

#### Beat 02 — Revenue Quality
*How much of revenue does the agency actually retain after pass-through costs?*

**Key Metrics:** Monthly AGI, AGI as a percentage of revenue

**Aha Moment:** AGI percentage reveals the service model. A 90%+ AGI agency is running a pure labor model — almost all value comes from people, not media or platforms. A 70% AGI agency is running significant pass-through costs. Neither is inherently better, but each implies different margin structures, client relationships, and team efficiency benchmarks. AGI% is the single most important efficiency signal in this tab.

---

#### Beat 03 — Profitability
*Is this agency pricing its work appropriately and managing costs with discipline?*

**Key Metrics:** Operating profit margin, monthly operating profit, monthly operating expenses

**Aha Moment:** Margin percentage shows financial discipline and pricing power. A 30%+ margin at any revenue level suggests strong cost management and appropriate pricing. A sub-15% margin at any scale is a warning signal. Profitability is the clearest indicator of whether the agency has built a sustainable business model or is working very hard to stay flat.

---

#### Beat 04 — Financial Stability
*How much strategic flexibility does this agency have?*

**Key Metrics:** Cash available, cash runway (months), financial health self-assessment

**Aha Moment:** Cash runway is the most operationally urgent metric in this entire tab. A profitable agency with 0.5 months of runway cannot make strategic hiring decisions, cannot weather a client loss, and cannot invest in growth infrastructure. Cash runway translates profitability into actual strategic capacity. Healthy margin means nothing without corresponding liquidity.

---

#### Beat 05 — Financial Maturity
*How financially sophisticated and stable is this operation overall?*

**Key Metrics:** Synthesis of scale + AGI efficiency + profitability + cash position

**Aha Moment:** The synthesis of all four beats tells the overall financial story. A mature economic foundation combines healthy scale, efficient revenue capture, strong profitability, and adequate liquidity. Most agencies are strong on some dimensions and weak on others — the combination reveals the financial character and strategic constraints of the business.

---

### Benchmark Reference

| Metric | Critical | Acceptable | Healthy | Excellent |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| AGI % | <75% | 75–85% | 85–95% | 95%+ |
| Operating Margin | <15% | 15–20% | 20–30% | 30%+ |
| Cash Runway | <1 month | 1–3 months | 3–6 months | 6+ months |

### **AGI % Benchmarks:**

* **90-95%:** Pure labor services (consulting, design, strategy)  
* **85-90%:** Balanced mix (some media, mostly labor)  
* **75-85%:** Media-heavy or platform-fee models  
* **\<75%:** Very high pass-through (media buying, platform reseller)

### **Profit Margin Benchmarks:**

* **30%+:** Excellent (strong discipline, pricing power)  
* **20-30%:** Healthy (sustainable, reinvestment capacity)  
* **15-20%:** Acceptable (tight but viable)  
* **10-15%:** Concerning (limited runway, vulnerable)  
* **\<10%:** Critical (unsustainable without changes)

### **Revenue Scale Complexity Bands:**

* **\<$1.5M:** Solo/micro (founder-led, minimal infrastructure)  
* **$1.5M-$3M:** Small (emerging systems, early specialization)  
* **$3M-$10M:** Established small (formalized processes, management layer)  
* **$10M-$10M:** Mid-size (departmentalization, significant infrastructure)  
* **$10M+:** Large (full executive team, complex operations)

### **Cash Runway Benchmarks:**

* **6+ months:** Very healthy (strategic flexibility)  
* **3-6 months:** Healthy (standard cushion)  
* **1-3 months:** Tight (limited flexibility)  
* **\<1 month:** Critical (vulnerable)

---

### Ownership Boundaries

| ✅ This Tab OWNS | 🚫 Cannot Tell Alone |
|---|---|
| Business size and revenue scale | Team efficiency → needs Delivery Architecture data |
| Revenue efficiency (AGI %) | Client economics → needs Revenue Model data |
| Operating profit margin | Revenue per FTE → needs Delivery Architecture team size |
| Cash position and runway | Growth sustainability → needs Revenue Model churn data |
| Overall financial health signal | |

