## Lens 3: Revenue Model
*Tab 3 of 4 · Client economics and revenue dynamics · Reveals how money flows and who sends it*

> **Core Question:** How does money flow into your business, who are your clients, how long do they stay, how do you attract them, and how dependent are you on key relationships?

---

### What This Lens Is Really Doing

Revenue Model captures how the business **earns its revenue and who it earns it from**. The name shift from "Growth & Pipeline" is intentional and important. "Pipeline" implies forward motion — something you are filling, growth you are pursuing. But at the snapshot level we are not asking about pipeline volume, lead generation metrics, or growth targets. We are asking about the **current revenue model and client dynamics** as they exist today.

This lens answers the revenue character question: how money flows in, how long it stays, how predictable it is, and how dependent the business is on any particular relationship or channel. It is a **business model description**, not a performance assessment.

---

### The 5 Story Beats

#### Beat 01 — Client Economics
*How valuable are your clients and what does that reveal about your service complexity?*

**Key Metrics:** Average Client Value (ACV), average client lifetime, active client count

**Aha Moment:** ACV is the single most revealing metric in this tab. It signals client complexity, service depth, relationship type, and operational requirements all at once. A $500/month ACV agency and a $15,000/month ACV agency are running fundamentally different businesses even if their total revenue is identical. ACV directly implies team structure, founder involvement requirements, and the appropriate sales and delivery model.

---

#### Beat 02 — Revenue Stability
*How predictable and stable is the revenue base?*

**Key Metrics:** MRR percentage, project revenue percentage, MRR vs. project split

**Aha Moment:** The recurring-to-project ratio reveals business model stability. A 70%+ MRR agency has a predictable foundation and can plan forward with confidence. A project-heavy agency faces feast/famine dynamics and must maintain constant pipeline activity even with excellent retention. The split also connects directly back to the pricing model described in Market Footprint — consistency between pricing model and revenue mix is itself an insight.

---

#### Beat 03 — Retention & Replacement Pressure
*How hard must this agency work just to stay flat?*

**Key Metrics:** Monthly churn rate, annual churn rate, replacement revenue calculation

**Aha Moment:** This is the most important insight in the Revenue Model tab and one of the most important in the entire snapshot. Many founders do not realize how much churn creates hidden growth requirements. At 3% monthly churn, an agency must generate 36% of its revenue in new business annually just to maintain current scale — before a single dollar of actual growth. This replacement treadmill reframes every growth conversation and sets up a critical cross-tab connection at the dashboard level.

---

#### Beat 04 — Acquisition Efficiency
*How does this agency attract new clients and how efficient is that process?*

**Key Metrics:** Primary acquisition channels (ranked), win rate, average sales cycle length

**Aha Moment:** Acquisition channel mix reveals the growth model. Referral-heavy agencies grow through relationships and network cultivation. Content or paid acquisition agencies grow through systems and spend. Each has different scalability profiles, cost structures, and ceiling dynamics. Win rate and sales cycle together reveal sales efficiency. A 40% win rate over a 2-month cycle is a very different acquisition profile than a 20% win rate over a 6-month cycle, even if total new revenue is similar.

---

#### Beat 05 — Client Concentration Risk
*How dependent is this business on its most valuable relationships?*

**Key Metrics:** Top 5 client revenue concentration, concentration risk classification

**Aha Moment:** Revenue concentration reveals structural vulnerability. An agency with 70% of revenue in 5 clients has a fundamentally different risk profile than one with 70% of revenue distributed across 30 clients. Concentration risk is especially meaningful when read alongside cash runway from Economic Foundation — a concentrated revenue base and thin cash runway together create significant exposure to client churn events.

---

### Benchmark Reference

| Metric | Concerning | Acceptable | Healthy | Excellent |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Monthly Churn | >3.5% | 2.5–3.5% | 2–2.5% | <2% |
| MRR Percentage | <40% | 40–60% | 60–80% | 80%+ |
| Win Rate | <20% | 20–30% | 30–40% | 40%+ |
| Top 5 Concentration | >70% | 50–70% | 30–50% | <30% |

---

### Ownership Boundaries

| ✅ This Tab OWNS | 🚫 Cannot Tell Alone |
|---|---|
| Client economics (ACV, lifetime value) | Team efficiency serving those clients → Delivery Architecture |
| Revenue stability (MRR vs. project split) | Profitability per client → needs Economic Foundation margin data |
| Retention health (churn, replacement pressure) | Whether acquisition model can scale → Dashboard cross-tab |
| Acquisition efficiency (channels, win rate, cycle) | Service positioning driving ACV → Market Footprint connection |
| Client concentration risk | |

---

### Dashboard Handoff Flags
*These insights require cross-tab data and only appear in the Dashboard synthesis:*

- 🔄 Replacement revenue requirement vs. cash runway (Revenue Model + Economic Foundation) — shows if liquidity can survive churn pressure
- 🔄 ACV complexity vs. team structure (Revenue Model + Delivery Architecture) — validates whether delivery model matches client complexity
