## Lens 4: Delivery Architecture
*Tab 4 of 4 · Human capital and operational structure · How the agency is built to do the work*

> **Core Question:** How is your agency structured to deliver services — how many people, in what configuration, at what efficiency, and how founder-dependent is the operation?

---

### What This Lens Is Really Doing

Delivery Architecture captures how the agency is **structurally built to do the work**. The name shift from "Team & Delivery" to "Delivery Architecture" is intentional. "Architecture" implies intentional structural design rather than just headcount. We are not evaluating delivery quality or operational efficiency as a performance metric. We are capturing the **structural composition of the delivery engine** — how it is built, not how well it is running.

This lens answers the organizational DNA question: how is the human capital investment configured, where are the leverage points, and where are the dependencies and constraints that define the operational ceiling of the business.

---

### The 5 Story Beats

#### Beat 01 — Team Scale & Efficiency
*How much value does each person on this team generate?*

**Key Metrics:** Total team FTE, AGI per FTE (calculated cross-tab from Economic Foundation)

**Aha Moment:** AGI per FTE is the primary efficiency signal for this tab. It reveals whether the agency is extracting healthy value from its human capital investment or carrying excess overhead. At a given revenue level, a smaller team generating high AGI per FTE signals a lean, high-leverage model. A larger team generating lower AGI per FTE signals either a service-complexity-driven structure (which may be appropriate) or operational inefficiency (which is a concern).

---

#### Beat 02 — Operational Leverage
*Is the agency structured with the right ratio of doers to managers and support?*

**Key Metrics:** Billable staff count, non-billable staff count, billable:non-billable ratio

**Aha Moment:** The billable-to-non-billable ratio reveals operational leverage. A 3:1 ratio means 3 revenue-generating people for every 1 overhead person. This is the structural efficiency indicator — it shows whether the agency has built appropriate infrastructure without excess overhead. Both extremes have implications: a 5:1 ratio may indicate under-investment in support functions, while a 1.5:1 ratio suggests top-heavy management structure.

---

#### Beat 03 — Delivery Model Complexity
*How complex is the delivery structure and what does that imply about coordination overhead?*

**Key Metrics:** Team structure type (generalist/specialist/hybrid), key roles present, management layers

**Aha Moment:** Delivery model type combined with management layers creates a complexity profile. A generalist team with 1–2 layers is nimble and simple. A specialist team with 3+ layers is sophisticated and complex. Neither is inherently better — complexity should match client complexity. A specialist model serving $500/month clients is over-engineered. A generalist model serving $15,000/month enterprise clients is under-equipped. Alignment between delivery complexity and ACV (from Revenue Model) is a key cross-tab signal.

---

#### Beat 04 — Founder Dependency
*Is the agency built to scale or is it built around the founder?*

**Key Metrics:** Founder time allocation, key leadership roles present

**Aha Moment:** Founder involvement in delivery is the single most common constraint on agency scale. An agency where the founder spends most time on client work is structurally capped at roughly $1–1.5M AGI — not because of market limitations but because the founder's time is finite. This beat reveals where on the delegation spectrum the agency currently sits and whether the leadership infrastructure exists to support further transition. The transition from "client work" to "strategy/sales" founder time is the inflection point that unlocks the next growth phase.

---

#### Beat 05 — Capacity Dynamics
*Does this agency have headroom to grow or is it already at capacity?*

**Key Metrics:** Utilization rate (if tracked), contractor count, self-assessed capacity constraint

**Aha Moment:** Capacity headroom is the growth enabler or constraint that makes replacement revenue and growth targets real or theoretical. An agency at 90% utilization with no contractors and no hiring pipeline cannot grow — regardless of how healthy its margins or retention look. Capacity context gives meaning to the growth math that emerges at the dashboard level when Economic Foundation, Revenue Model, and Delivery Architecture combine.

---

### Benchmark Reference

| Metric | Concerning | Acceptable | Healthy | Excellent |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| AGI per FTE (monthly) | <$12K | $12K–$15K | $15K–$20K | $20K+ |
| Billable:Non-Billable | <2:1 | 2:1–2.5:1 | 2.5:1–4:1 | 4:1 lean |
| Founder Time | Mostly delivery | Mix delivery/ops | Mostly ops | Strategy/sales |

---

### Ownership Boundaries

| ✅ This Tab OWNS | 🚫 Cannot Tell Alone |
|---|---|
| Team size and scale | Profitability per team member → needs Economic Foundation margin data |
| Team efficiency (AGI per FTE) | Revenue per FTE → needs Economic Foundation revenue data |
| Operational leverage (billable ratio) | Client load per person → needs Revenue Model client count |
| Delivery model complexity | Payroll as % of revenue → needs Economic Foundation payroll + revenue |
| Founder dependency level | Whether capacity matches growth targets → Dashboard cross-tab |
| Capacity constraints and headroom | |

---

